Links: [{"title":"[Issue] Custom provider baseurl, return opencode.json is invalid Required provider.anthropic.models · Issue #5428 · anomalyco/opencode","url":"https://github.com/anomalyco/opencode/issues/5428"},{"title":"Custom @ai-sdk/anthropic provider loads correctly but drops API key at runtime when using custom baseURL · Issue #21737 · anomalyco/opencode","url":"https://github.com/anomalyco/opencode/issues/21737"},{"title":"Custom baseURL configuration returns \"Route /api/messages not found\" error · Issue #5163 · anomalyco/opencode","url":"https://github.com/anomalyco/opencode/issues/5163"},{"title":"Config | OpenCode","url":"https://opencode.ai/docs/config/"},{"title":"OpenCode Configuration - MegaLLM","url":"https://docs.megallm.io/en/agents/opencode"},{"title":"OpenCode Custom Provider Setup: Add Any OpenAI-Compatible API | haimaker.ai Blog","url":"https://haimaker.ai/blog/opencode-custom-provider-setup/"}]

Based on the search results, here's how to configure a custom provider base URL for Anthropic in OpenCode's `opencode.json`:

## Basic Configuration

The configuration goes in `~/.config/opencode/opencode.json` (global) or `opencode.json` in your project directory. Config sources are loaded in this order (later sources override earlier ones): Remote config, Global config (~/.config/opencode/opencode.json), Custom config (OPENCODE_CONFIG env var), and Project config (opencode.json in project).

The basic structure for a custom Anthropic base URL looks like this:

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://opencode.ai/config.json",
  "provider": {
    "anthropic": {
      "options": {
        "apiKey": "{env:YOUR_API_KEY}",
        "baseURL": "https://your-custom-url/v1"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Important: `models` is now required

A key change to be aware of: in newer versions, the `models` field is **required**. One user reported that after upgrading to version 0.3.133, the previously working config that only set `baseURL` under `options` produced an error: "Config file is invalid ↳ Required provider.anthropic.models".

To fix this, you must include a `models` section. Some gateways auto-populate it — for example, with MegaLLM, the CLI automatically fetches and populates the models from the provider. But to be safe, define them explicitly:

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://opencode.ai/config.json",
  "provider": {
    "anthropic": {
      "options": {
        "apiKey": "{env:MY_API_KEY}",
        "baseURL": "https://your-endpoint/v1"
      },
      "models": {
        "claude-sonnet-4-5": { "name": "Claude Sonnet 4.5" }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Using a custom provider ID (recommended approach)

Rather than overriding the built-in `anthropic` provider, you can define a fully custom provider using the npm package. For an Anthropic-native API: use `"npm": "@ai-sdk/anthropic"` with a name, options containing `baseURL` and `apiKey`, and a `models` object.

For OpenAI-compatible endpoints, use `@ai-sdk/openai-compatible` instead:

```json
{
  "$schema": "https://opencode.ai/config.json",
  "provider": {
    "my-provider": {
      "npm": "@ai-sdk/openai-compatible",
      "name": "My Provider",
      "options": {
        "baseURL": "https://api.example.com/v1",
        "apiKey": "{env:MY_API_KEY}"
      },
      "models": {
        "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6": { "name": "Claude Sonnet 4.6" }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## Troubleshooting tips

A few common pitfalls from the search results:

- **API key handling:** Do not include "Bearer" in the key field. Note that there's a reported bug where a custom @ai-sdk/anthropic provider with a custom baseURL loads and the model can be selected, but at runtime the request fails with a 401 invalid_request_error stating no API key was provided. If you hit this, an OpenAI-compatible endpoint may be a workaround.

- **404 / route errors:** If you set a custom `baseURL` and get a "Not Found" error, check that your endpoint path is correct — one user encountered a "Route /api/messages not found" / Not Found error with a custom baseURL. Often the trailing path segment (e.g., `/v1`) matters depending on whether the gateway expects the Anthropic messages path.

- **General checklist:** Make sure the provider ID from `opencode auth login` matches the provider key in config, the config file is valid JSON or JSONC, you restarted OpenCode after editing provider config, and the model is listed under the provider's models object.

For the full configuration reference, the official documentation is at `https://opencode.ai/docs/config/`.


